05813nam a22007695i 9780813564340DE-B159720221205051307.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221205t20152015nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135643407 a10.36019/97808135643402doi  a(DE-B1597)529986  a(OCoLC)914255807  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.4302/822300aActing /ced. by Julie Levinson, Claudia Springer. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b42 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBehind the Silver Screen Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Silent Screen, 1895–1927 -- t2. Classical Hollywood, 1928–1946 -- t3. Postwar Hollywood, 1947–1967 -- t4. The Auteur Renaissance, 1968–1980 -- t5. The New Hollywood, 1981–1999 -- t6. The Modern Entertainment Marketplace, 2000–Present -- tAcademy Awards for Acting -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aScreen performances entertain and delight us but we rarely stop to consider actors’ reliance on their craft to create memorable characters. Although film acting may appear effortless, a host of techniques, artistic conventions, and social factors shape the construction of each role. The chapters in Acting provide a fascinating, in-depth look at the history of film acting, from its inception in 1895 when spectators thrilled at the sight of vaudeville performers, Wild West stars, and athletes captured in motion, to the present when audiences marvel at the seamless blend of human actors with CGI. Experts in the field take readers behind the silver screen to learn about the craft of film acting in six eras: the silent screen (1895–1928), classical Hollywood (1928–1946), postwar Hollywood (1947–1967), the auteur renaissance (1968–1980), the New Hollywood (1981–1999), and the modern entertainment marketplace (2000–present). The contributors pay special attention to definitive performances by notable film stars, including Lillian Gish, Dick Powell, Ginger Rogers, Beulah Bondi, Marilyn Monroe, Marlon Brando, Jack Nicholson, Robert De Niro, Nicholas Cage, Denzel Washington, and Andy Serkis. In six original essays, the contributors to this volume illuminate the dynamic role of acting in the creation and evolving practices of the American film industry. Acting is a volume in the Behind the Silver Screen series—other titles in the series include Animation; Art Direction and Production Design; Cinematography; Costume, Makeup, and Hair; Directing; Editing and Special/Visual Effects; Producing; Screenwriting; and Sound.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aMotion picture acting. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  ascreen performance, performing arts, acting, audition, actor, actress, silver screen, social science, media studies, film, video, communications, history of film, film acting, performer, performance, vaudeville, wild west, hollywood, cgi, athlete, audience, movie goers, silent screen, classical hollywood, postwar hollywood, auteur renaissance, new hollywood, modern entertainment marketplace, entertainment, lillian gish, dick powell, ginger rogers, beulah bondi, marilyn monroe, marlon brando, jack nicholson, robert de niro, nicholas cage, denzel washington, andy serkis, academy awards, oscars.1 aBaron, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuckett, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevinson, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevinson, Julie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNolletti, Arthur,